<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06359207 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06359207 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Associated Press; EMPTY HOUSE -- A delegate to the Sovietparliament was alone with his thoughts today as the end draws near (color).;PHOTO: Gorbachev (color)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  USSR; GOVERNMENT; CHANGE; LEADER; RESIGN; COUNTRY; POLITICS  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Mikhail Gorbachev said goodbye to his Kremlin staff today and is expected toannounce his resignation during the Wednesday evening news program on CentralTelevision, the Russian Information Agency said today.;   On Saturday, 11 ofthe 12 former Soviet republics proclaimed a new Commonwealth of IndependentStates to replace the Soviet Union and agreed to allow Russia, by far thelargest and most populous republic, to assume the U.N. Security Council seat.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FAREWELL TO GORBACHEVEXPECTED TO QUIT ON WEDNESDAY  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     In the strongest indication yet about what Gorbachev would do, therespected daily newspaper Izvestia said Monday he was considering chairmanshipof a 4-month-old Fund for Socio-Political Research.;   The fund employs about200 people and has mainly prepared analyses for Russian and former Sovietofficials.;   The remnants of the national legislature -- only about one-thirdof lawmakers -- met today, but put off blessing the new commonwealth. Itagreed without taking a vote to hold its final session after the next meetingof the new commonwealth Dec. 30.;   But the lawmakers then decided toreconvene at an afternoon session, said Zheken K. Kaliev, a deputy fromKazakhstan.;   It was not clear if they would take up a resolutionacknowledging the demise of the Soviet Union or whether Gorbachev wouldattend.;   In Washington, the Bush administration said the United States wouldextend diplomatic recognition to Russia as an independent country, probablyThursday when President Bush returns from a three-day Christmas vacation atCamp David, Md.;   The United States will recognize the independence of theother republics that have broken with Moscow and formed the commonwealth butfor now will establish diplomatic relations with only &quot;about half&quot; therepublics, said an administration official.;   The United States will wait tosee how the others perform in adhering to democratic rule, respect for therights of minorities and other principles that the United States hasenunciated as a condition to recognition, the official said.;   RussianPresident Boris Yeltsin called Bush on Monday to press for recognition. Theadministration official said the decision to do so was &quot;inevitable.&quot;;   &quot;Itreflects the reality of the situation in the Soviet Union -- the old SovietUnion,&quot; he said.;   Robert Strauss, the U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union,will become ambassador to Russia, the official said.;   Gorbachev met withYeltsin on Monday to discuss the transfer of power and was expected to resignin &quot;the next 24 hours,&quot; said Russian First Deputy Prime Minister GennadyBurbulis.;   Press spokesman Alexei Kozhemyakov said Gorbachev met with his 30remaining staff members today to bid them farewell and discuss &quot;practicalquestions of transformation of the state and some practical issues of ourwork.&quot;;   In a newspaper interview published today, Gorbachev reiterated hiscriticism of the new commonwealth, saying it was unclear whether it was &quot;aunification or a fragmentation.&quot;;   Gorbachev told Komsomolskaya Pravda heworried about unrest if the economy and living conditions continue to worsenbut said he did not expect another military coup.;   In their meeting,Gorbachev and Yeltsin discussed the orderly transfer of command over the lateSoviet Union's 27,000 nuclear weapons and other issues of succession.;   Theissue of who controls the nuclear &quot;button&quot; has been one of the most pressingquestions since Gorbachev's central government collapsed in the wake of thefailed August coup.;   Gorbachev late Monday gave British Prime Minister JohnMajor &quot;a great deal of reassurance&quot; that the weapons were under tight controland would remain that way, Major said.;   The commonwealth will assume controlover the Soviet military while letting other central government functions dieor be handed over to republics.;   As part of the new commonwealth agreement,the four nuclear republics -- Ukraine, Byelorussia, Kazakhstan and Russia --agreed to let Yeltsin keep the briefcase with codes and communicationsequipment needed to launch the weapons, although the decision to launch mustbe collective.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Moscow  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911224  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  661  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, December 24, 199100359207,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENGFRONT  </LANGUAGE></DOC>